From 5c18b8aaa2aa3bcf9735f84fc4a30725fe4fcd44 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Matthew Feickert <matthew.feickert@cern.ch>
Date: Wed, 6 May 2026 07:17:11 -0600
Subject: [PATCH] fix: replace 'isnan' macro with std::isnan calls

The '#define isnan(x) std::isnan(x)' macro in src/utils.h is a
function-like macro whose name is 'isnan'. When the C++ standard
library writes 'std::isnan(__x.imag())' from inside namespace std
(e.g. libc++ 19's <complex>), the preprocessor sees 'isnan(' as a
macro invocation and expands it, producing 'std::std::isnan(...)',
which fails to parse with 'no member named std in namespace std'.

The macro was a portability shim for getting std::isnan into the
unqualified namespace; pyne now requires C++11 unconditionally, so
'std::isnan' is always available. Replace each call site with the
properly qualified call and drop the macro definitions, including
the legacy non-GCC and Windows fallbacks.

Reproduced on conda-forge osx-64 with libcxx-headers 19.1.7
when compiling Cython 3-generated files that include <complex>.
